  "prompt": "What's the difference between slugs and snails, besides the shell?",
  "response": "Here are some key differences between slugs and snails beyond just the shell:\n\n1. Body structure\n- Slugs have a more elongated, soft body\n- Snails have a more compact body due to their shell\n\n2. Movement\n- Slugs move directly on their muscular body\n- Snails carry and move with their shell, which affects their locomotion\n\n3. Protection\n- Slugs lack a hard external shell and rely more on mucus for protection\n- Snails have a hard calcium carbonate shell for physical protection\n\n4. Habitat preference\n- Slugs tend to prefer damper, more hidden environments\n- Snails can tolerate slightly drier conditions due to their shell\n\n5. Predator defense\n- Slugs rely more on camouflage and hiding\n- Snails can retreat fully into their shell when threatened\n\n6. Water retention\n- Slugs lose moisture more quickly and need very moist environments\n- Snails' shells help them retain moisture better\n\n7. Metabolism\n- Slugs generally have a faster metabolism\n- Snails can slow down metabolic processes and seal their shell opening during dry periods\n\nBoth are gastropod mollusks and share many similarities in diet and basic biology, but these differences distinguish them.",
